        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-07-19T15:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-07-19T15:57:00-05:00" n="201"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                <head>201. Memorandum of a Telephone Conversation Between the President and the
                    Secretary of State, Washington, July 19, 1958, 4:57 p.m.<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d201fn1">Source: Eisenhower Library, Dulles Papers,
                        White House Telephone Conversations. Transcribed in the Secretary’s office
                        by <persName corresp="#p_BPD1">Phyllis D. Bernau</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1958-07-19T16:57:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1958, 4:57 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">TELEPHONE CALL TO THE PRESIDENT</p>
                <p>The Sec said the 9 prisoners are released.<note n="2" xml:id="d201fn2">Apparent
                        reference to the release of a U.S. helicopter crew which had been held for a
                        month in East Germany.</note> He told re the message from <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d201fn3">See
                            <ref target="#d200">
                            <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> The premise is we are committing aggression. We have not
                    received the full text as yet. The Sec’s reaction is negative—he thinks it is a
                    propaganda stunt but we will study it. The Sec had a talk with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MC9">Malik</persName>.<note n="4" xml:id="d201fn4">See <ref
                            target="#d198">Document 198</ref>.</note> They are kind of anxious to
                    drag us into this thing in a bigger way—the Sec told him we are not going to do
                    it. We are there for one purpose—the integrity and independence of Lebanon—if
                    that is taken care of then we leave etc. He is seeing the Yugoslav at 5<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d201fn5">Reference is to the Chargé of the Yugoslav Embassy;
                        the conversation is summarized <ref target="#d202">
                            <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> and then <persName corresp="#p_LJSB1">Lloyd</persName> at
                    5:30. He will talk with <persName corresp="#p_LJSB1">Lloyd</persName> about the
                    message from K and see what his reaction is—and let the Pres know later on.</p>
            </div>
